You can break it down similar to how you would decompose a decimal number into the 1s place, 10s place 100s place, etc.

To get the 1s place you would take the remainder when dividing by 10 (ie num % 10).

To get the 10s place you would first divide by 10, then repeat the same process: (num / 10) % 10 .

To get the 100s place you would first divide by 100, then repeat the same process: (num / 100) % 10 .

In your example, you are not using base 10, but rather base 2^8. Therefore, you will need to adjust 10 to be 2^8 and 100 (or 10*10) to be 2^16 (or 2^8*2^8), etc.

What you end up with is something like:

    fourLetterWord[0] = sum          % 2^8;
    fourLetterWord[1] = (sum / 2^8)  % 2^8;
    fourLetterWord[2] = (sum / 2^16) % 2^8;
    fourLetterWord[3] = (sum / 2^24) % 2^8;

